        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2"> Bleh.  My personal feeling is that DC is a little much, but not so much that it needs to be reduced to uselessness.  I honestly haven't seen it used in a raid, and don't have it, so take this with a grain of salt.  :)  The balance of damage-dealing needs to be maintained; but as to whether DC threatens that, and if so how much, isn't something I can say for certain.</P><P>But what I do know...whoever said that nerfing DC won't fix mages is right on the mark.  Whether DC is overpowered or not is an issue of general game balance; removing the DC'd pet from a fight still leaves plenty of classes that will blow mage pets away in damage.  Trying to fix mages in this manner would basically be lowering everyone to the lowest common denominator, making every encounter significantly harder and taking lots of balance work (as you can easily break things in the process of adjusting them).  Address the problem directly -- if something is worse than it should be, boost it.</P><P>Much of the mage complaining here seems to follow the sort of "possessive" class envy you see sometimes...that is, a bunch of players get angry that something that was unique to them, or partially so, is given out, even if only symbolically, and even if it has little effect on the balance of their class.  Like when some Clerics complained about us getting Convergence -- it doesn't threaten them in the least, but it still offended them.  Overall game balance is a much greater issue than being able to say you're the master of whatever.</P><P>And, a thought...what if mages could have some kind of unstable summon, that calls forth a powerful mob that that has the chance to break free of the mage's control?  ie: summon one of the lesser mobs in a zone, and make start out with a charm effect that attaches it to the mage.  No, this isn't DC, but for those situations where charm itself is very powerful, this might give mages something comparable.  Of course, the downside is that the mage can't regain control of the mob once it breaks...but if the mob is considered summoned and is low enough level, it could be banished by a 60 mage or druid.  (level limit on that spell is 45...?  anyone know?)</P><P><img src="http://members.aol.com/jrimdziustemp/chickencult.gif">   Aatudien, 58 necromancer of Lanys T'Vyl<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height=15 width=15 border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
